\section{General resummation formula}

In general, a path-ordered exponential with an integrand depending on a
single variable $\xi_0$ can be rewritten in the following way:

\begin{eqnarray}
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_0[B(\xi_0)+C(\xi_0)]\right\}
&=&
\sum_{l=0}^\infty
\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_1\int^{\xi_1}_{y_0}d\xi_2...\int^{\xi_{l-1}}_{y_0}d\xi_l
~\nonumber \\
&~&
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{\xi_1}^{x_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
C(\xi_1)
\times
~\nonumber \\
&\times&
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{\xi_2}^{\xi_1}d\xi_0B(\xi_0)\right\}
C(\xi_2)
\times
~\nonumber \\
&\times&
...
\times
~\nonumber \\
&\times&
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{\xi_l}^{\xi_{l-1}}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
C(\xi_l)
\times
~\nonumber \\
&\times&
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{y_0}^{\xi_l}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}.
\end{eqnarray}

Making use of the group property valid for the present path-ordered 
exponentials:

\begin{eqnarray}
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{z_0}^{x_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
\times
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{y_0}^{z_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
=
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{y_0}^{x_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
\label{addth}
\end{eqnarray}

the above equation can be reexpressed as:

\begin{eqnarray}
&{\cal P}\exp&\left\{\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_0[B(\xi_0)+C(\xi_0)]\right\}
=
~\nonumber \\~\nonumber \\
=
&{\cal P}\exp&\left\{\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_0B(\xi_0)\right\}
\sum_{l=0}^\infty
\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_1\int^{\xi_1}_{y_0}d\xi_2...\int^{\xi_{l-1}}_{y_0}d\xi_l
\times
~\nonumber \\
\times
&{\cal P}\exp&\left\{\int_{x_0}^{y_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{\xi_1}^{x_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
C(\xi_1)
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int^{\xi_1}_{y_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
\times
~\nonumber \\
\times
&{\cal P}\exp&\left\{\int_{x_0}^{y_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{\xi_2}^{x_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
C(\xi_2)
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int^{\xi_2}_{y_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
\times
...
\times
~\nonumber \\
\times
&{\cal P}\exp&\left\{\int_{x_0}^{y_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{\xi_l}^{x_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
C(\xi_l)
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int^{\xi_l}_{y_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
=
~\nonumber \\~\nonumber \\
=
&{\cal P}\exp&\left\{\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
\times
~\nonumber \\
&&\times
{\cal P}\exp\left[
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{x_0}^{y_0}dz_0 B(z_0)\right\}\right.
\times
~\nonumber \\
&&~~~~~\times
\left.\int_{x_0}^{y_0}d\xi_0
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{\xi_0}^{x_0}dz_0 B(z_0)\right\}
C(\xi_0)
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int^{\xi_0}_{y_0}dz_0 B(z_0)\right\}
\right].
~\nonumber \\
\label{general}
\end{eqnarray}

Again, by virtue of the group property the most compact form is given by:

\begin{eqnarray}
&{\cal P}\exp&\left\{\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_0[B(\xi_0)+C(\xi_0)]\right\}
=
~\nonumber \\
=
&{\cal P}\exp&\left\{\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_0 B(\xi_0)\right\}
\times
~\nonumber \\
\times
&{\cal P}\exp&\left[
\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_0
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int_{\xi_0}^{y_0}dz_0 B(z_0)\right\}
C(\xi_0)
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int^{\xi_0}_{y_0}dz_0 B(z_0)\right\}
\right].
\label{resumgen}
\end{eqnarray}

Summarising, 
more general resummations are possible in which the dominant quantity can be
chosen arbitrarily. Further, the above steps can be repeated so as to 
resum the obtained quantity several times, e.g. after splitting $C(\xi_0)$
into a dominant part and a deviation.

The above result can also be obtained in another way. Write the Fourier
transformed Dirac equation in a generic form, where the dependence
on $\vec k$ will not be denoted in the following:

\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\frac{d}{dx_0}+B(x_0)+C(x_0)\right] G_H(x_0,y_0)=0.
\label{genericdirac}
\end{eqnarray}

With the ansatz

\begin{eqnarray}
 G_H(x_0,y_0)=U(x_0,y_0)\hat G_H(x_0,y_0)
\end{eqnarray}

and the product rule for differentiation one obtains:

\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\frac{d}{dx_0}U(x_0,y_0)\right]\hat G_H(x_0,y_0)
+
U(x_0,y_0)\left[\frac{d}{dx_0}\hat G_H(x_0,y_0)\right]
+
~\nonumber \\
+
\left[B(x_0)+C(x_0)\right]U(x_0,y_0)\hat G_H(x_0,y_0)
=0.
\end{eqnarray}

When postulating that $U(x_0,y_0)$ satisfies the differential equation

\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{d}{dx_0}U(x_0,y_0)+B(x)U(x_0,y_0)=0,
\label{link}
\end{eqnarray}

the above expression reduces to:

\begin{eqnarray}
U(x_0,y_0)\left[\frac{d}{dx_0}\hat G_H(x_0,y_0)\right]
+
C(x_0)U(x_0,y_0)\hat G_H(x_0,y_0)
=0.
\end{eqnarray}

This formula can be transformed by multiplying with $U^{-1}(x_0,y_0)$ from the
left:

\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\frac{d}{dx_0}\hat G_H(x_0,y_0)\right]
+
U^{-1}(x_0,y_0)C(x_0)U(x_0,y_0)\hat G_H(x_0,y_0)
=0.
\end{eqnarray}

As has been shown above, the solutions for the last equation and equation 
(\ref{link}) are given by

\begin{eqnarray}
\hat G(x_0,y_0)
=
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_0
U^{-1}(\xi_0,y_0)C(\xi_0)U(\xi_0,y_0)
\right\}
\end{eqnarray}

and

\begin{eqnarray}
U(x_0,y_0)
=
{\cal P}\exp\left\{\int^{x_0}_{y_0}d\xi_0
B(\xi_0) 
\right\},
\end{eqnarray}

respectively. Making use of the group property (\ref{addth}) the last line 
of equation (\ref{general}) is reproduced. These derivations can be repeated
for any variable $n\cdot x$. Only for $n^2=0$ the Dirac equation cannot be written in
the generic form (\ref{genericdirac}).


